          "text": "Now I have a complete picture. Here's my analysis:\n\n## Why rindexer needs Node.js\n\nThe **sole reason** is the **GraphQL server**. Specifically:\n\n### `graphql/index.js` — A Node.js Express + PostGraphile server\n\nThe GraphQL API is a standalone Node.js application that uses:\n- **PostGraphile v4** — auto-generates a GraphQL API from PostgreSQL schemas\n- **Express** — HTTP server\n- **pg** — PostgreSQL client\n- Plugins: `pg-simplify-inflector`, `postgraphile-plugin-connection-filter`\n\n### How it's integrated\n\n1. **Build time** (`core/build.rs`): During `cargo build`, the build script:\n   - Checks that `node` and `npm` are installed (panics if not)\n   - Runs `npm install` in the `graphql/` directory\n   - Uses [`@yao-pkg/pkg`](https://github.com/nicolo-ribaudo/pkg) to compile the Node.js app into a **standalone binary** (e.g. `rindexer-graphql-macos-arm64`) targeting Node 22\n   - Embeds the binary into the Rust binary via `include_bytes!`\n\n2. **Runtime** (`core/src/api/graphql.rs`): The Rust code:\n   - Extracts the embedded Node binary to a temp path (or uses the build path in dev)\n   - Spawns it as a child process with connection string, schemas, port, etc. as CLI args\n   - Health-checks it via HTTP, then proxies users to it\n\n### The result\nrindexer ships a ~50MB+ Node.js binary **baked into** the Rust binary. Node.js is needed at build time but NOT at runtime (the `pkg`-compiled binary is self-contained).\n\n---\n\n## Options to remove the Node.js dependency\n\nThe core question is: **can PostGraphile be replaced with a pure-Rust GraphQL server?**\n\n| Option | Effort | Description |\n|--------|--------|-------------|\n| **1. Rust PostGraphile equivalent** | **High** | No direct Rust equivalent of PostGraphile exists. You'd need to build auto-introspection of PG schemas → GraphQL schema generation, which is PostGraphile's main value. Libraries like `async-graphql` or `juniper` are manual schema builders, not introspectors. |