          "text": "Here's how reorg handling works for latest blocks:\n\n## Yes — latest blocks are held in memory via two caches\n\n### 1. LRU Block Cache (primary, real-time)\n**`core/src/indexer/fetch_logs.rs:457`** — a fixed-size LRU cache of 1024 entries:\n\n```rust\nlet mut block_cache: LruCache<u64, BlockMeta> = LruCache::new(NonZeroUsize::new(1024).unwrap());\n```\n\nEach entry stores `BlockMeta { hash, parent_hash, timestamp }`. This is used for two detection strategies:\n\n- **Tip hash change** (line ~538): if the cache already has a hash for block N and the new poll returns a different hash for block N → reorg\n- **Parent hash mismatch** (line ~561): if block N+1's `parent_hash` doesn't match the cached hash for block N → reorg\n\nOn reorg, affected entries are evicted: `block_cache.pop(&b)` for each orphaned block number.\n\n### 2. Shadow Cache (secondary, delayed verification)\n**`core/src/indexer/reorg.rs:1306-1308`** — an unbounded `HashMap<u64, B256>` behind a Mutex:\n\n```rust\npub type ShadowCache = Arc<std::sync::Mutex<std::collections::HashMap<u64, B256>>>;\n```\n\nThis mirrors the block cache in real-time but is checked by a background verifier every **30 seconds**. It only verifies blocks with **64+ confirmations**, comparing cached hashes against canonical RPC hashes. Verified blocks are pruned; mismatches trigger reorg recovery. This catches **silent reorgs** the real-time layer might miss.\n\n### 3. Two additional non-memory layers\n\n- **Reth chain state notifications** (`fetch_logs.rs:433-450`) — feature-gated, receives explicit `Reorged`/`Reverted` events from a Reth node\n- **RPC `removed` flag** (`fetch_logs.rs:751-795`) — standard JSON-RPC mechanism where providers mark logs on reorged blocks\n\n### Recovery flow\n\nWhen any layer detects a reorg:\n1. `find_fork_point()` walks backward through the block cache (up to 64 blocks) comparing against canonical RPC hashes\n2. Orphaned events are deleted from Postgres/ClickHouse for blocks >= fork point\n3. Internal checkpoints are rewound\n4. Derived tables are cleaned and optionally replayed\n5. Block cache entries for orphaned blocks are evicted\n\n### Potential concern with the shadow cache\n\nThe shadow cache (`HashMap`) is **unbounded** — it only gets pruned when blocks reach 64 confirmations and the verifier runs. On a fast chain (e.g. Polygon at ~2s blocks), that's ~32 unverified entries accumulating per minute. In practice this stays small (a few thousand entries at most), but it's worth noting there's no hard cap unlike the LRU cache.\n\nWant me to dig deeper into any specific layer or look at a potential issue?",
